You can create a class in C# to store student information and provide methods to read and modify the information. Here's an example code that accomplishes this:

```csharp
public class Student
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public int Age { get; set; }
    public string Gender { get; set; }

    public Student(){ }

    public Student(string name, int age, string gender)
    {
        Name = name;
        Age = age;
        Gender = gender;
    }

    public void SetName(string name){ Name = name; }
    public void SetAge(int age){ Age = age; }
    public void SetGender(string gender){ Gender = gender; }
    public string GetName(){ return Name; }
    public int GetAge(){ return Age; }
    public string GetGender() { return Gender; }
}
```

In this code, a class named `Student` is defined with three properties: `Name`, `Age`, and `Gender`. These properties have both getter and setter methods, allowing you to read and modify the information stored in each property.

The class also has two constructors: a default constructor and a parameterized constructor. The default constructor doesn't take any arguments and can be used to create an empty `Student` object. The parameterized constructor takes three arguments (`name`, `age`, and `gender`) and initializes the corresponding properties when creating a new `Student` object.

Additionally, the class provides methods to set and get the values of the `Name`, `Age`, and `Gender` properties. The `SetName`, `SetAge`, and `SetGender` methods are used to modify the values, while the `GetName`, `GetAge`, and `GetGender` methods are used to retrieve the values.

You can create a new `Student` object and use these methods to read and modify the student's information as needed.

According to the MSDN documentation for `System.Reflection.Assembly.ReflectionOnlyLoad (String)`, unloading an assembly is only possible by unloading the application domain. Therefore, the only way to unload an assembly is by unloading the application domain. To achieve this, you can create a new `AppDomain` and load the necessary assemblies into it.

Here's an example of how you can implement this:

```csharp
public void TempLoadAssembly()
{
    AppDomain tempDomain = AppDomain.CreateDomain("TemporaryAppDomain");
    tempDomain.DoCallBack(LoaderCallback);
    AppDomain.Unload(tempDomain);
}

private void LoaderCallback()
{
    Assembly.ReflectionOnlyLoad("YourAssembly");
    // Perform your operations here
}
```

In the `TempLoadAssembly` method, a new `AppDomain` named "TemporaryAppDomain" is created. Then, the `DoCallBack` method is used to execute the `LoaderCallback` method within the temporary `AppDomain`. Inside the `LoaderCallback` method, you can use `Assembly.ReflectionOnlyLoad` to load the desired assembly and perform any necessary operations.

By unloading the temporary `AppDomain` using `AppDomain.Unload(tempDomain)`, you ensure that the loaded assembly is also unloaded.

This solution should work for both assemblies on the file system and those at URL addresses.

You can use the following code snippet to check if a given string consists of only digits in C#:

```csharp
public static bool IsDigitsOnly(string str)
{
    // Check each character in the string
    foreach (char c in str)
    {
        // If it is a non-digit character, return false
        if (!Char.IsDigit(c))
            return false;
    }

    // Otherwise, the string consists of only digits
    return true;
}
```

In this code, the `IsDigitsOnly` function takes a string `str` as a parameter. It then iterates through each character in the string using a foreach loop. Inside the loop, it checks if the current character is a digit using the `Char.IsDigit` method. If a non-digit character is found, the function immediately returns `false` as the string does not consist of only digits.

If all characters pass the digit check, the function returns `true`, indicating that the string consists of only digits.

You can call this function by passing your desired string as an argument. The function will return `true` if the string only contains digits and `false` otherwise.

Example usage:

```csharp
string input = "12345";
bool result = IsDigitsOnly(input);
Console.WriteLine(result);  // Output: True

string input2 = "abc123";
bool result2 = IsDigitsOnly(input2);
Console.WriteLine(result2); // Output: False
```

By calling the `IsDigitsOnly` function with different input strings, you can easily determine if a given string consists of only digits.

You can use the following code to generate a JavaScript class that keeps track of a shopping list:

```javascript
class ShoppingList {
  constructor() {
    this.list = [];
  }

  addItem(item) {
    this.list.push(item);
  }

  removeItem(index) {
    this.list.splice(index, 1);
  }

  getList() {
    return this.list;
  }
}
```

This code defines a class called `ShoppingList` with three important methods. The constructor initializes an empty array called `list`, which will store the items in the shopping list.

The `addItem(item)` method allows you to add a new item to the shopping list. It takes an `item` parameter and uses the `push()` method to add the item to the end of the `list` array.

The `removeItem(index)` method allows you to remove an item from the shopping list. It takes an `index` parameter and uses the `splice()` method to remove the item at the specified index from the `list` array.

The `getList()` method simply returns the current shopping list stored in the `list` array.

By utilizing this class, you can easily manage a shopping list in your JavaScript application.
